SIMPLE: illness
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Illness
<hw>Ill"ness</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From
<er>Ill</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The condition of being ill, evil,
or bad; badness; unfavorableness.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧The
<xex>illness</xex> of the weather.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Locke.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Disease; indisposition; malady; disorder of health;
sickness; <as>as, a short or a severe <ex>illness</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Wrong moral conduct; wickedness.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Malady; disease; indisposition; ailment.</syn>
<usage> -- <er>Illness</er>, <er>Sickness</er>. Within the present
century, there has been a tendency in England to use <xex>illness</xex>
in the sense of a continuous disease, disorder of health, or sickness,
and to confine <xex>sickness</xex> more especially to a sense of nausea,
or ⟦ldquo⟧sickness of the stomach.⟦rdquo⟧</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ill-nurtured</ent>⟦br⟧
